Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the finest relics of this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the tour guides tell you.
The building stands on a horseback at the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking out at the world like some German provincial town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the ceiling to the vault, there is no doubt about the greatness of the enterprise of what was the most westerly passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a backward in the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions of dominating the Middle East by this railway that ran to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
The relative isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed
British and dominating forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station too.
In 1917 a train of ammunition exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was a sabotage.
Since then it has been slowly decaying, largely outdated by history.
But today, this railway exit to Anatolia and all the points to the east, serve - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever-growing diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Its isolation from its surrounding regions, caused by the icy borders of the Cold War, is over.
Now there's a new commitment policy.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the bed car to Ankara, the Turkish capital, to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a run of skid skates along the tracks that produced the ancient world sequences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intended to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in Turkish consensus.
He's suggested some suspicion in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure - built on purpose - in a developing suburb, surrounded by built-up shopping malls and power bakeries, where business executives - both men and women - meet to make early morning contracts.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry too.
"The foreign policy party's goal now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its land.
