The bee car to avoid collisions
In developing accident prevention technologies, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, and especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, for example, by flying bees, can avoid accidents.
It's the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of the Nissan four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is designed to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicles of the manufacturer.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing is the bees' compound eyes, which can see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly uninterrupted in its personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, engineers have developed what they call a localization laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within two metres and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor that immediately prevents collision.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels at a right or higher angle to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If it wasn't, the robot wouldn't be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate up or down, nor even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can turn and not by exploiting endless directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid collisions.
"This device just needs to process the information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It doesn't require the storing of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruptions and with only a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, and we're not talking about mega".
It is the first step towards developing new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to get the driver to their destination avoiding obstacles along the way.
