Morgan Stanley has announced that it has signed an agreement with Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the first bank in Japan, to invest $9 billion in a 21 percent stake in the company, following a sharp decline in its stock market shares.
A week after the provisional agreement was drawn up, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley's shares at an individual cost of $25.25, or a sum equal to $3 billion.
The price established is 19% lower than the book value of the securities at 31 August.
MUFG will also invest $6 billion in the purchase of convertible securities at a conversion price of $31.25, providing a return of 10%.
Morgan Stanley has stated that the global transaction would be carried out on the basis of an average price of $29 per share, or a percentage below its current price of 28%.
At 5 p.m., however, Morgan Stanley stock was down 6.79% to $23.07.
"This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to a bank holding company", explained John Mack, the group's US CEO.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to diversify its stock and yet bring it under the control of the Federal Reserve.
The agreement with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to take a much more cautious stance than previously assumed.
The arrangements set out on Monday also show that the agreement has been amended in recent days: last Monday, Morgan simply announced the sale of 20% of its shares to the Japanese giant for a sum of $8.5 billion.
"A week ago, in Tokyo, Toshihide Mizuno, executive director of MUFG, explained: "We thought our stake would be solely of ordinary shares.
