The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions who were abducted 10 days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive in the desert for 10 days were returned to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon, safe and sound.
In the morning, they were liberated in Chad by an Egyptian command.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at the Almaza military base near Cairo International Airport at about 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft.
On board a helicopter, they were immediately transferred, without being able to give any press interviews, to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for analysis.
They are in "good health" and no ransom has been paid "to the hijackers", said the Egyptian Minister of Tourism, Zoheir Garanna, on the runway.
Kidnapped on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been unloaded from hiding place to hiding place by 35 unknown kidnappers.
