Benelux governments nationalize a part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries are helping through partial nationalization the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which has been in trouble for the first time in Europe due to the American credit market crisis: the three nations will provide EUR 11.2 billion to the financial institution - insurance with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level over the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
The first major crisis in the euro area in the context of the difficulties facing the international financial market for more than a year is that of Fortis Bank, and in some respects the decisions taken in this regard can set a precedent.
Under the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank's share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch company ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis' stock had started collapsing vertically, and serious signs of the institute's crisis were showing up later in the second half of the week.
Analysts agree, however, that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank's shares fell nearly 12 percent on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
The total capital value of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the bank's management this is not real.
The company's top blames the collapse of Fortis shares on uncertainties in the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US$700 billion plan.
The headline picked up again on Monday.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The financial institution has also sought out private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a worthy offer.
The Belgian government had already assured investors that they should not fear losing money.
The bank's customers were not panicked, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary Fortis owns independent subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people's medical billing data, often refuse to take out an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
'There is a privacy programme whereby the use of prescription data depends on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it's like entrusting the chicken to the fox", writes the Washington Post, citing Richard Dick, author of the program to follow prescriptions for medicines.
Insurance companies shall subordinate the insurance rate and the surcharge in case of accidents to the health status of the potential customer and if they consider the risk too high they shall not provide insurance.
A long time ago the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was only concluded after the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure 10 years ago: the customer's identification code can easily give you information from pharmacies about which medicines he has bought in the last year and a half and from that the program shows which diseases he suffers from and what health conditions he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, that means that your blood fat level is virtually undeniably high and you're classified as the highest risk category.
There are several versions of the programme on the market, some of which also determine the risk multiplier, the insurer, so apart from paperwork, there is not much left, even if there are minor difficulties.
Some medicines are used for multiple purposes, such as some compounds are used against migraines or heat stroke, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is a risk-increasing factor from an insurance-commercial point of view, while the first two are not.
Separate companies have been formed to request and process data and before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies they ask for the patient's approval.
Now the authorities are forcing you to do so even though they have not imposed fines for negligence so far.
Some companies have also recently processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to data on drug use to provide a more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time, controlling usage will become increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but it only applies to health services and insurance.
There is a bill before Congress that gives authorities control over data services firms.
Richard Dick admits that this is not enough: he has therefore developed a programme that links the data forwarding with the express approval of the person concerned.
The other issue is that the person concerned cannot so much as deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not stipulate the contract.
So then the chickens are finally entrusted to the fox's mercy.
