EU and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are mainly trading partners, this theme was also the agenda of the ninth summit, as well as all other global issues.
Today there will be a French-Indian summit, which will focus primarily on cooperation on nuclear energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is becoming a major democratic power and should be given more voice in international affairs, but member countries have yet to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So this was not the issue that was raised at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, acting President of the Union, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received the Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade in five years, i.e. increase it to EUR 100 billion.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods increased from 25 to 55 billion, this is not an ambitious target.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil aviation agreements, so air traffic can also start in the future.
India would like to sign the Free Trade Agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the deal.
The aim is to balance because while the EU is India's top trading partner, New Delhi is only the ninth among the EU partners.
